{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DiFb4yLEQ92GEu2jEmyJeC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see! There's no `es-cluster` StatefulSet. The `es-nodes` StatefulSet appears to be the main cluster. This is an inherited cluster from previous stages (the precondition saw 12 Running pods and skipped the full rebuild). \n\nThe case `seed-hosts-repair` uses `BENCH_PARAM_CLUSTER_PREFIX=es-cluster`, but the actual StatefulSet in the cluster is `es-nodes`. This is because the case's precondition was skipped (probe succeeded = pods running), and a different stage had already deployed `es-nodes`.\n \nI'm checking the precondition logic more carefully. The probe command counted 12 Running pods, which means the probe succeeded. Since the precondition has `on_probe_fail: skip`, a successful probe means the apply step gets skipped—the environment is already set up. But I need to trace which precondition unit this is and what it's actually setting up. stage_07 is also `seed-hosts-repair`, and since the probe succeeded with 12 pods running, the precondition skipped the apply step. But the fault should still be present for the test to work, so I need to trace back through the cluster state—maybe something changed during stage_06's scale-up operation that affected the fault scenario. Let me check what the oracle actually verifies to understand what state I'm looking for.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2715,"cache_read_input_tokens":41747,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2715},"output_tokens":45,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a9894363-34c2-4ba1-a8f4-f8ca4b3b113b","uuid":"833f141c-ecc1-4bb6-84db-b4903d9f90d2","request_id":"req_011Cc8aFuDEoypXBAWygfapV"}
