{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Q84r7sHs38T585Bh2MpPoG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. The `app-data` index exists and has 1 document. The cluster is green with 5 nodes.\n\nNow let me think about what the oracle will check:\n1. Cluster health yellow/green → PASS (green)\n2. `number_of_nodes == expected_nodes (3)` → FAIL (5 != 3)\n3. `len(node_names) == expected_nodes (3)` → FAIL (5 != 3)\n4. `app-data` count check → PASS\nThe oracle will fail on the node count mismatch since we have 5 nodes but expected 3. But the scenario says a node failed to rejoin after restart, which suggests we should have fewer nodes, not more. Let me look at how the oracle determines the expected node count—it checks environment variables for the expected count, then falls back to calculating it from the cluster spec.\n\nThe fallback sums up the replicas from all Elasticsearch StatefulSets that have active replicas, which would give us 9 total across all clusters. That's clearly wrong. The key insight is that the code should only count StatefulSets that actually back the live cluster, not all StatefulSets in the system.\n\nI'm noticing that `_live_sts_names` is defined to extract the StatefulSet names from the actual node names, but it doesn't seem to be used in the fallback path. The comment says restricting to the live cluster's StatefulSets fixes the overcounting problem, but the actual code iterates through all StatefulSets without that filtering. The function takes `node_names` as a parameter but never actually uses it when checking the environment variable, and the code doesn't filter to only the live StatefulSets like the comment claims it should—it's counting all Elasticsearch StatefulSets regardless of which cluster they belong to.\n\nSince `BENCH_PARAM_EXPECTED_NODE_COUNT=3` is set, the oracle expects 3 nodes but the cluster has 5, so the oracle will fail. But looking at the actual StatefulSet readiness, all pods are accounted for—es-nodes has 3 ready replicas and es-data has 2 ready replicas, so there's no missing node to restore.\n\nLet me reconsider the precondition setup for stage_07. The first unit's probe passed and was logged, but I'm not seeing output from the second unit. Either it ran silently because its probe passed and apply was skipped, or the log was truncated and only the first unit executed so far.\n\nLooking at the timestamps might clarify whether the precondition ran recently or if there's a timing mismatch with when the pods were actually created.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":544,"cache_read_input_tokens":66041,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":544},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a9894363-34c2-4ba1-a8f4-f8ca4b3b113b","uuid":"30e4a7ed-accb-4f4d-b190-45b2fb799222","request_id":"req_011Cc8aXgp4TTxpHHyxAEsPh"}
